					<span class="printuser avatarhover"><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/greenwolf" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(1814684); return false;"  ><img class="small" src="http://www.wikidot.com/avatar.php?userid=1814684&amp;amp;size=small&amp;amp;timestamp=1610252392" alt="GreenWolf" style="background-image:url(http://www.wikidot.com/userkarma.php?u=1814684)"/></a><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/greenwolf" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(1814684); return false;" >GreenWolf</a></span> <span class="odate time_1486521290 format_%25e%20%25b%20%25Y%2C%20%25H%3A%25M%7Cagohover">08 Feb 2017 02:34</span>
														</div>
			</div>
			<div class="content" id="post-content-2742416">
									

<p>I wasn't a fan of the Secure Facilities dossiers when they first popped up last year, and this does nothing to change that. As a hub, it's overly complicated to navigate, and as a tale, it's uninteresting.</p>
<p>Also, building a moonbase on the near side of the Moon is possibly one of the dumbest things an organization dedicated to preserving normalcy could possibly do. We can <em>see</em> the surface of the Moon here on Earth, and even amateur telescopes can see things as small as the Apollo landing sites. (To clarify, not the landers themselves, but the craters they landed in. Initial post saying &quot;landers&quot; was a mistype.) You might be able to edit the images taken by the LRO and other space-based assets, but you can't edit the eyeballs of everyone in the world with a telescope, no matter your resources.</p>
<p>It's basically like sticking a giant billboard in the sky that says &quot;HERE WE ARE.&quot;</p>

							</div>

								
