			<div class="content" id="post-content-2742423">
									

<blockquote>
<p>We can see the surface of the Moon here on Earth, and even amateur telescopes can see things as small as the Apollo landers.</p>
</blockquote>
<p>No. Very, very, wrong.</p>
<p><a href="http://www.skyandtelescope.com/observing/celestial-objects-to-watch/moon/how-to-see-all-six-apollo-moon-landing-sites/">This page has pictures a satellite orbiting the moon took of the Apollo landing sites</a>. The few-pixel-wide specks are vehicles about the size of a compact car. Again, that's a satellite in low orbit around the moon with a camera intended to photograph said sites. Even Hubble can't resolve anything smaller than a city block on the lunar surface from Earth orbit.</p>
<p>Basically, you could build a theme park on the Moon and no one would know except maybe a couple space programs if they were actively looking for it.</p>

							</div>

								
