			</div>
			<div class="content" id="post-content-2742426">
									

<blockquote>
<p>Even Hubble can't resolve anything smaller than a city block on the lunar surface.</p>
</blockquote>
<p>This is not because Hubble can't see the landing sites (it can resolve down to about 90 meters at that distance, theoretically), it is because <em>Hubble is moving too fast to take clear pictures of the moon.</em> This is also true of most orbiting telescopes trying to take photos of planets. <a href="https://what-if.xkcd.com/32/">Randall Munroe has more info about this here.</a></p>
<p>This is one of the few cases where ground-based telescopes <em>are</em> better.</p>
<p>Also, consider for a moment that the size of this base is stated as being over <em>14 square kilometers</em>. That is <em>easily</em> resolved by even handheld telescopes.</p>

							</div>

								
