														</div>
			</div>
			<div class="content" id="post-content-2742430">
									

<p>I think you are ignoring the part about it being <em>14 square kilometers</em>. That is much larger than a city block, and would be visible with <em>binoculars</em>.</p>
<blockquote>
<p>There's a reason those photos I linked to are the first time we've been able to confirm that the landing sites weren't trashed by the takeoff of the return stage.</p>
</blockquote>
<p>This is untrue. We've been bouncing lasers off the retroreflectors left at the landsites for literally decades now.</p>
<p>Also keep in mind that a base such as this will be emitting a lot of heat and radio communications, which just makes it even <em>easier</em> to spot. During the Apollo program, amateur radio operators were able to pick up their transmissions.</p>

							</div>

								
