			<div class="content" id="post-content-2742439">
									

<p>Yes, true on the laser thing, but they intentionally put those a fair distance away from the lander because they wanted to be sure that they weren't damaged.</p>
<p><a href="http://curious.astro.cornell.edu/about-us/45-our-solar-system/the-moon/the-moon-landings/122-are-there-telescopes-that-can-see-the-flag-and-lunar-rover-on-the-moon-beginner">Here's another article on the subject that includes that calculations</a>. Apparently you'd need a 25m telescope to see the landing modules from Earth. Running the same calculation, you'd need a 7cm telescope to have any chance of seeing a 3km x 3km structure from Earth in ideal conditions, assuming you knew exactly where to look and they made no attempt whatsoever to hide it by something like, say, piling a layer of moon dust across it.</p>

							</div>

								
					
